# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: pointer-authentication
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] Due to their low costs, low power consumption, and low heat generation, ARM processors are useful for light, portable, battery-powered devices, including smartphones, laptops, and tablet computers, as well as embedded systems.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] However, ARM processors are also used for desktops and servers, including Fugaku, the world's fastest supercomputer from 2020 to 2022.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] With over 230 billion ARM chips produced, since at least 2003, and with its dominance increasing every year, ARM is the most widely used family of instruction set architectures.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] There have been several generations of the ARM design.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] The original ARM1 used a 32-bit internal structure but had a 26-bit address space that limited it to 64 MB of main memory.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] This limitation was removed in the ARMv3 series, which has a 32-bit address space, and several additional generations up to ARMv7 remained 32-bit.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] Released in 2011, the ARMv8-A architecture added support for a 64-bit address space and 64-bit arithmetic with its new 32-bit fixed-length instruction set.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] Arm Holdings has also released a series of additional instruction sets for different roles: the "Thumb" extensions add both 32- and 16-bit instructions for improved code density, while Jazelle added instructions for directly handling Java bytecode.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] More recent changes include the addition of simultaneous multithreading (SMT) for improved performance or fault tolerance.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] Acorn Computers' first widely successful design was the BBC Micro, introduced in December 1981.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] This was a relatively conventional machine based on the MOS Technology 6502 CPU but ran at roughly double the performance of competing designs like the Apple II due to its use of faster dynamic random-access memory (DRAM).
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] Typical DRAM of the era ran at about 2 MHz; Acorn arranged a deal with Hitachi for a supply of faster 4 MHz parts.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] Machines of the era generally shared memory between the processor and the framebuffer, which allowed the processor to quickly update the contents of the screen without having to perform separate input/output (I/O).
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] As the timing of the video display is exacting, the video hardware had to have priority access to that memory.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] Due to a quirk of the 6502's design, the CPU left the memory untouched for half of the time.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] Thus by running the CPU at 1 MHz, the video system could read data during those down times, taking up the total 2 MHz bandwidth of the RAM.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] In the BBC Micro, the use of 4 MHz RAM allowed the same technique to be used, but running at twice the speed.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] This allowed it to outperform any similar machine on the market.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] 1981 was also the year that the IBM Personal Computer was introduced.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] Using the recently introduced Intel 8088, a 16-bit CPU compared to the 6502's 8-bit design, it offered higher overall performance.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] Its introduction changed the desktop computer market radically: what had been largely a hobby and gaming market emerging over the prior five years began to change to a must-have business tool where the earlier 8-bit designs simply could not compete.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] Even newer 32-bit designs were also coming to market, such as the Motorola 68000 and National Semiconductor NS32016.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] Acorn began considering how to compete in this market and produced a new paper design named the Acorn Business Computer.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] They set themselves the goal of producing a machine with ten times the performance of the BBC Micro, but at the same price.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] This would outperform and underprice the PC.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] At the same time, the recent introduction of the Apple Lisa brought the graphical user interface (GUI) concept to a wider audience and suggested the future belonged to machines with a GUI.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] The Lisa, however, cost $9,995, as it was packed with support chips, large amounts of memory, and a hard disk drive, all very expensive then.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] The engineers then began studying all of the CPU designs available.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] Their conclusion about the existing 16-bit designs was that they were a lot more expensive and were still "a bit crap", offering only slightly higher performance than their BBC Micro design.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] They also almost always demanded a large number of support chips to operate even at that level, which drove up the cost of the computer as a whole.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] These systems would simply not hit the design goal.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] They also considered the new 32-bit designs, but these cost even more and had the same issues with support chips.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] According to Sophie Wilson, all the processors tested at that time performed about the same, with about a 4 Mbit/s bandwidth.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] Two key events led Acorn down the path to ARM.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] One was the publication of a series of reports from the University of California, Berkeley, which suggested that a simple chip design could nevertheless have extremely high performance, much higher than the latest 32-bit designs on the market.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] The second was a visit by Steve Furber and Sophie Wilson to the Western Design Center, a company run by Bill Mensch and his sister Kathryn, which had become the logical successor to the MOS team and was offering new versions like the WDC 65C02.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] The Acorn team saw high school students producing chip layouts on Apple II machines, which suggested that anyone could do it.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] In contrast, a visit to another design firm working on modern 32-bit CPU revealed a team with over a dozen members who were already on revision H of their design and yet it still contained bugs.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] This cemented their late 1983 decision to begin their own CPU design, the Acorn RISC Machine.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] The original Berkeley RISC designs were in some sense teaching systems, not designed specifically for outright performance.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] To the RISC's basic register-heavy and load/store concepts, ARM added a number of the well-received design notes of the 6502.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] Primary among them was the ability to quickly service interrupts, which allowed the machines to offer reasonable input/output performance with no added external hardware.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] To offer interrupts with similar performance as the 6502, the ARM design limited its physical address space to 64 MB of total addressable space, requiring 26 bits of address.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] As instructions were 4 bytes (32 bits) long, and required to be aligned on 4-byte boundaries, the lower 2 bits of an instruction address were always zero.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] This meant the program counter (PC) only needed to be 24 bits, allowing it to be stored along with the eight bit processor flags in a single 32-bit register.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] That meant that upon receiving an interrupt, the entire machine state could be saved in a single operation, whereas had the PC been a full 32-bit value, it would require separate operations to store the PC and the status flags.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] This decision halved the interrupt overhead.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] Another change, and among the most important in terms of practical real-world performance, was the modification of the instruction set to take advantage of page mode DRAM.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] Recently introduced, page mode allowed subsequent accesses of memory to run twice as fast if they were roughly in the same location, or "page", in the DRAM chip.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] Berkeley's design did not consider page mode and treated all memory equally.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] The ARM design added special vector-like memory access instructions, the "S-cycles", that could be used to fill or save multiple registers in a single page using page mode.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] This doubled memory performance when they could be used, and was especially important for graphics performance.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] The Berkeley RISC designs used register windows to reduce the number of register saves and restores performed in procedure calls; the ARM design did not adopt this.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] Wilson developed the instruction set, writing a simulation of the processor in BBC BASIC that ran on a BBC Micro with a second 6502 processor.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] This convinced Acorn engineers they were on the right track.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] Wilson approached Acorn's CEO, Hermann Hauser, and requested more resources.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] Hauser gave his approval and assembled a small team to design the actual processor based on Wilson's instruction set architecture.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] The official Acorn RISC Machine project started in October 1983.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] Acorn chose VLSI Technology as the "silicon partner", as they were a source of ROMs and custom chips for Acorn.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] Acorn provided the design and VLSI provided the layout and production.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] The first samples of ARM silicon worked properly when first received and tested on 26 April 1985.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] Known as ARM1, these versions ran at 6 MHz.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] The first ARM application was as a second processor for the BBC Micro, where it helped in developing simulation software to finish development of the support chips (VIDC, IOC, MEMC), and sped up the CAD software used in ARM2 development.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] Wilson subsequently rewrote BBC BASIC in ARM assembly language.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] The in-depth knowledge gained from designing the instruction set enabled the code to be very dense, making ARM BBC BASIC an extremely good test for any ARM emulator.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] ARM Evaluations Systems featuring ARM1 CPUs and supplied as second processors for BBC Micro and Master machines, were made available from July 1986 under the Acorn OEM Products brand to developers and researchers.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] The A500 Second Processor, an additional ARM1 based BBC Micro and Master second processor, featured the ARM support chipset (VIDC, IOC, MEMC), was capable of producing video output and operating near independently of the host BBC Micro.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] The result of the simulations on the ARM1 boards led to the late 1986 introduction of the ARM2 design running at 8 MHz, and the early 1987 speed-bumped version at 10 to 12 MHz.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] A significant change in the underlying architecture was the addition of a Booth multiplier, whereas formerly multiplication had to be carried out in software.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] Further, a new Fast Interrupt reQuest mode, FIQ for short, allowed registers 8 to 14 to be replaced as part of the interrupt itself.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] This meant FIQ requests did not have to save out their registers, further speeding interrupts.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] The first use of the ARM2 was in internal Acorn A500 development machines, and the Acorn Archimedes personal computer models A305, A310, and A440, launched on the 6th June 1987.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] According to the Dhrystone benchmark, the ARM2 was roughly seven times the performance of a typical 7 MHz 68000-based system like the Amiga or Macintosh SE.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] It was twice as fast as an Intel 80386 running at 16 MHz, and about the same speed as a multi-processor VAX-11/784 superminicomputer.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] The only systems that beat it were the Sun SPARC and MIPS R2000 RISC-based workstations.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] Further, as the CPU was designed for high-speed I/O, it dispensed with many of the support chips seen in these machines; notably, it lacked any dedicated direct memory access (DMA) controller which was often found on workstations.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] The graphics system was also simplified based on the same set of underlying assumptions about memory and timing.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] The result was a dramatically simplified design, offering performance on par with expensive workstations but at a price point similar to contemporary desktops.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] The ARM2 featured a 32-bit data bus, 26-bit address space and 27 32-bit registers, of which 16 are accessible at any one time (including the PC).
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] The ARM2 had a transistor count of just 30,000, compared to Motorola's six-year-older 68000 model with around 68,000.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] Much of this simplicity came from the lack of microcode, which represents about one-quarter to one-third of the 68000's transistors, and the lack of (like most CPUs of the day) a cache.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] This simplicity enabled the ARM2 to have a low power consumption and simpler thermal packaging by having fewer powered transistors.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] Nevertheless, ARM2 offered better performance than the contemporary 1987 IBM PS/2 Model 50, which initially utilised an Intel 80286, offering 1.8 MIPS @ 10 MHz, and later in 1987, the 2 MIPS of the PS/2 70, with its Intel 386 DX @ 16 MHz.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] A successor, ARM3, was produced with a 4 KB cache, which further improved performance.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] The address bus was extended to 32 bits in the ARM6, but program code still had to lie within the first 64 MB of memory in 26-bit compatibility mode, due to the reserved bits for the status flags.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 1988, Sanyo became a worldwide second source for the ARM2 and associated chipset under an agreement with VLSI Technology.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] In the late 1980s, Apple Computer and VLSI Technology started working with Acorn on newer versions of the ARM core.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 1990, Acorn spun off the design team into a new company named Advanced RISC Machines Ltd., which became ARM Ltd. when its parent company, Arm Holdings plc, floated on the London Stock Exchange and Nasdaq in 1998.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] The new Apple–ARM work would eventually evolve into the ARM6, first released in early 1992.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] Apple used the ARM6-based ARM610 as the basis for their Apple Newton PDA.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 1994, Acorn used the ARM610 as the main central processing unit (CPU) in their RiscPC computers.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] DEC licensed the ARMv4 architecture and produced the StrongARM.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] At 233 MHz, this CPU drew only one watt (newer versions draw far less).
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] This work was later passed to Intel as part of a lawsuit settlement, and Intel took the opportunity to supplement their i960 line with the StrongARM.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] Intel later developed its own high performance implementation named XScale, which it has since sold to Marvell.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] Transistor count of the ARM core remained essentially the same throughout these changes; ARM2 had 30,000 transistors, while ARM6 grew only to 35,000.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 2005, about 98% of all mobile phones sold used at least one ARM processor.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 2010, producers of chips based on ARM architectures reported shipments of 6.1 billion ARM-based processors, representing 95% of smartphones, 35% of digital televisions and set-top boxes, and 10% of mobile computers.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 2011, the 32-bit ARM architecture was the most widely used architecture in mobile devices and the most popular 32-bit one in embedded systems.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 2013, 10 billion were produced and "ARM-based chips are found in nearly 60 percent of the world's mobile devices".
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] Arm Holdings's primary business is selling IP cores, which licensees use to create microcontrollers (MCUs), CPUs, and systems-on-chips based on those cores.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] The original design manufacturer combines the ARM core with other parts to produce a complete device, typically one that can be built in existing semiconductor fabrication plants (fabs) at low cost and still deliver substantial performance.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] The most successful implementation has been the ARM7TDMI with hundreds of millions sold.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] Atmel has been a precursor design center in the ARM7TDMI-based embedded system.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] The ARM architectures used in smartphones, PDAs and other mobile devices range from ARMv5 to ARMv8-A.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 2009, some manufacturers introduced netbooks based on ARM architecture CPUs, in direct competition with netbooks based on Intel Atom.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] Arm Holdings offers a variety of licensing terms, varying in cost and deliverables.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] Arm Holdings provides to all licensees an integratable hardware description of the ARM core as well as complete software development toolset (compiler, debugger, software development kit), and the right to sell manufactured silicon containing the ARM CPU.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] SoC packages integrating ARM's core designs include Nvidia Tegra's first three generations, CSR plc's Quatro family, ST-Ericsson's Nova and NovaThor, Silicon Labs's Precision32 MCU, Texas Instruments's OMAP products, Samsung's Hummingbird and Exynos products, Apple's A4, A5, and A5X, and NXP's i.MX.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] Fabless licensees, who wish to integrate an ARM core into their own chip design, are usually only interested in acquiring a ready-to-manufacture verified semiconductor intellectual property core.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] For these customers, Arm Holdings delivers a gate netlist description of the chosen ARM core, along with an abstracted simulation model and test programs to aid design integration and verification.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] More ambitious customers, including integrated device manufacturers (IDM) and foundry operators, choose to acquire the processor IP in synthesizable RTL (Verilog) form.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] With the synthesizable RTL, the customer has the ability to perform architectural level optimisations and extensions.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] This allows the designer to achieve exotic design goals not otherwise possible with an unmodified netlist (high clock speed, very low power consumption, instruction set extensions, etc.).
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] While Arm Holdings does not grant the licensee the right to resell the ARM architecture itself, licensees may freely sell manufactured products such as chip devices, evaluation boards and complete systems.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] Merchant foundries can be a special case; not only are they allowed to sell finished silicon containing ARM cores, they generally hold the right to re-manufacture ARM cores for other customers.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] Arm Holdings prices its IP based on perceived value.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] Lower performing ARM cores typically have lower licence costs than higher performing cores.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] In implementation terms, a synthesisable core costs more than a hard macro (blackbox) core.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] Complicating price matters, a merchant foundry that holds an ARM licence, such as Samsung or Fujitsu, can offer fab customers reduced licensing costs.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] In exchange for acquiring the ARM core through the foundry's in-house design services, the customer can reduce or eliminate payment of ARM's upfront licence fee.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] Compared to dedicated semiconductor foundries (such as TSMC and UMC) without in-house design services, Fujitsu/Samsung charge two- to three-times more per manufactured wafer.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] For low to mid volume applications, a design service foundry offers lower overall pricing (through subsidisation of the licence fee).
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] For high volume mass-produced parts, the long term cost reduction achievable through lower wafer pricing reduces the impact of ARM's NRE (non-recurring engineering) costs, making the dedicated foundry a better choice.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] In February 2016, ARM announced the Built on ARM Cortex Technology licence, often shortened to Built on Cortex (BoC) licence.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] This licence allows companies to partner with ARM and make modifications to ARM Cortex designs.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] These design modifications will not be shared with other companies.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] These semi-custom core designs also have brand freedom, for example Kryo 280.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] Companies that are current licensees of Built on ARM Cortex Technology include Qualcomm.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] Companies can also obtain an ARM *architectural licence* for designing their own CPU cores using the ARM instruction sets.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] These cores must comply fully with the ARM architecture.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] Companies that have designed cores that implement an ARM architecture include Apple, AppliedMicro (now: Ampere Computing), Broadcom, Cavium (now: Marvell), Digital Equipment Corporation, Intel, Nvidia, Qualcomm, Samsung Electronics, Fujitsu, and NUVIA Inc.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] On 16 July 2019, ARM announced ARM Flexible Access.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] ARM Flexible Access provides unlimited access to included ARM intellectual property (IP) for development.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] Per product licence fees are required once a customer reaches foundry tapeout or prototyping.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] 75% of ARM's most recent IP over the last two years are included in ARM Flexible Access.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] ARMv3 included a compatibility mode to support the 26-bit addresses of earlier versions of the architecture.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] This compatibility mode is *optional* in ARMv4, and removed entirely in ARMv5.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] Arm provides a list of vendors who implement ARM cores in their design (application specific standard products (ASSP), microprocessor and microcontrollers).
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] ARM cores are used in a number of products, particularly PDAs and smartphones.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] Some computing examples are Microsoft's first generation Surface, Surface 2 and Pocket PC devices (following 2002), Apple's iPads, and Asus's Eee Pad Transformer tablet computers, and several Chromebook laptops.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] Others include Apple's iPhone smartphones and iPod portable media players, Canon PowerShot digital cameras, Nintendo Switch hybrid, the Wii security processor and 3DS handheld game consoles, and TomTom turn-by-turn navigation systems.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 2005, Arm took part in the development of Manchester University's computer SpiNNaker, which used ARM cores to simulate the human brain.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p01] ARM chips are also used in Raspberry Pi, BeagleBoard, BeagleBone, PandaBoard, and other single-board computers, because they are very small, inexpensive, and consume very little power.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] The 32-bit ARM architecture (**ARM32**), such as **ARMv7-A** (implementing AArch32; see section on Armv8-A for more on it), was the most widely used architecture in mobile devices as of 2011.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Although the architecture profiles were first defined for ARMv7, ARM subsequently defined the ARMv6-M architecture (used by the Cortex M0/M0+/M1) as a subset of the ARMv7-M profile with fewer instructions.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] 26-bit addressing - obsolete as of June 2000.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Multiply and multiply-accumulate instructions; coprocessor support - all variants obsolete as of June 2000.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] 32-bit addressing - all variants obsolete as of July 2005.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] , the former of which supports the 32-bit ARM instruction set, called A32, and the Thumb-2 instruction set, called T32, and the latter of which supports a new instruction set with 32 64-bit registers, called A64.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Except in the M-profile, the 32-bit ARM architecture specifies several CPU modes, depending on the implemented architecture features.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] At any moment in time, the CPU can be in only one mode, but it can switch modes due to external events (interrupts) or programmatically.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] The original ARM implementation was hardwired without microcode, like the much simpler 8-bit 6502 processor used in prior Acorn microcomputers.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] ARM includes integer arithmetic operations for add, subtract, and multiply; some versions of the architecture also support divide operations.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] ARM supports 32-bit × 32-bit multiplies with either a 32-bit result or 64-bit result, though Cortex-M0 / M0+ / M1 cores do not support 64-bit results.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Some ARM cores also support 16-bit × 16-bit and 32-bit × 16-bit multiplies.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Registers R0 through R7 are the same across all CPU modes; they are never banked.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Registers R8 through R12 are the same across all CPU modes except FIQ mode.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] FIQ mode has its own distinct R8 through R12 registers.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] R13 and R14 are banked across all privileged CPU modes except system mode.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] That is, each mode that can be entered because of an exception has its own R13 and R14.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] These registers generally contain the stack pointer and the return address from function calls, respectively.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Current Program Status Register (CPSR) has the following 32 bits.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Almost every ARM instruction has a conditional execution feature called predication, which is implemented with a 4-bit condition code selector (the predicate).
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] To allow for unconditional execution, one of the four-bit codes causes the instruction to be always executed.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Most other CPU architectures only have condition codes on branch instructions.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Though the predicate takes up four of the 32 bits in an instruction code, and thus cuts down significantly on the encoding bits available for displacements in memory access instructions, it avoids branch instructions when generating code for small `if` statements.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Apart from eliminating the branch instructions themselves, this preserves the fetch/decode/execute pipeline at the cost of only one cycle per skipped instruction.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] An algorithm that provides a good example of conditional execution is the subtraction-based Euclidean algorithm for computing the greatest common divisor.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] which avoids the branches around the `then` and `else` clauses.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] If `r0` and `r1` are equal then neither of the `SUB` instructions will be executed, eliminating the need for a conditional branch to implement the `while` check at the top of the loop, for example had `SUBLE` (less than or equal) been used.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] One of the ways that Thumb code provides a more dense encoding is to remove the four-bit selector from non-branch instructions.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] This results in the typical ARM program being denser than expected with fewer memory accesses; thus the pipeline is used more efficiently.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] The ARM processor also has features rarely seen in other RISC architectures, such as PC-relative addressing (indeed, on the 32-bit ARM the PC is one of its 16 registers) and pre- and post-increment addressing modes.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] The ARM instruction set has increased over time.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Some early ARM processors (before ARM7TDMI), for example, have no instruction to store a two-byte quantity.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] The ARM7 and earlier implementations have a three-stage pipeline; the stages being fetch, decode, and execute.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Higher-performance designs, such as the ARM9, have deeper pipelines: Cortex-A8 has thirteen stages.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Additional implementation changes for higher performance include a faster adder and more extensive branch prediction logic.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] The difference between the ARM7DI and ARM7DMI cores, for example, was an improved multiplier; hence the added "M".
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] The ARM architecture (pre-Armv8) provides a non-intrusive way of extending the instruction set using "coprocessors" that can be addressed using MCR, MRC, MRRC, MCRR, and similar instructions.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] The coprocessor space is divided logically into 16 coprocessors with numbers from 0 to 15, coprocessor 15 (cp15) being reserved for some typical control functions like managing the caches and MMU operation on processors that have one.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] In ARM-based machines, peripheral devices are usually attached to the processor by mapping their physical registers into ARM memory space, into the coprocessor space, or by connecting to another device (a bus) that in turn attaches to the processor.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Coprocessor accesses have lower latency, so some peripherals—for example, an XScale interrupt controller—are accessible in both ways: through memory and through coprocessors.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] In other cases, chip designers only integrate hardware using the coprocessor mechanism.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] For example, an image processing engine might be a small ARM7TDMI core combined with a coprocessor that has specialised operations to support a specific set of HDTV transcoding primitives.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] All modern ARM processors include hardware debugging facilities, allowing software debuggers to perform operations such as halting, stepping, and breakpointing of code starting from reset.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] These facilities are built using JTAG support, though some newer cores optionally support ARM's own two-wire "SWD" protocol.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] In ARM7TDMI cores, the "D" represented JTAG debug support, and the "I" represented presence of an "EmbeddedICE" debug module.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] For ARM7 and ARM9 core generations, EmbeddedICE over JTAG was a de facto debug standard, though not architecturally guaranteed.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] The ARMv7 architecture defines basic debug facilities at an architectural level.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] These include breakpoints, watchpoints and instruction execution in a "Debug Mode"; similar facilities were also available with EmbeddedICE.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Both "halt mode" and "monitor" mode debugging are supported.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] The actual transport mechanism used to access the debug facilities is not architecturally specified, but implementations generally include JTAG support.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] There is a separate ARM "CoreSight" debug architecture, which is not architecturally required by ARMv7 processors.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Debug Access Port (DAP) is an implementation of an ARM Debug Interface.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] There are two different supported implementations, the Serial Wire JTAG Debug Port (SWJ-DP) and the Serial Wire Debug Port (SW-DP).
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] CMSIS-DAP is a standard interface that describes how various debugging software on a host PC can communicate over USB to firmware running on a hardware debugger, which in turn talks over SWD or JTAG to a CoreSight-enabled ARM Cortex CPU.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] To improve the ARM architecture for digital signal processing and multimedia applications, DSP instructions were added to the instruction set.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] These are signified by an "E" in the name of the ARMv5TE and ARMv5TEJ architectures.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] The new instructions are common in digital signal processor (DSP) architectures.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] They include variations on signed multiply–accumulate, saturated add and subtract, and count leading zeros.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] First introduced in 1999, this extension of the core instruction set contrasted with ARM's earlier DSP coprocessor known as Piccolo, which employed a distinct, incompatible instruction set whose execution involved a separate program counter.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Piccolo instructions employed a distinct register file of sixteen 32-bit registers, with some instructions combining registers for use as 48-bit accumulators and other instructions addressing 16-bit half-registers.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Some instructions were able to operate on two such 16-bit values in parallel.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Communication with the Piccolo register file involved *load to Piccolo* and *store from Piccolo* coprocessor instructions via two buffers of eight 32-bit entries.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Described as reminiscent of other approaches, notably Hitachi's SH-DSP and Motorola's 68356, Piccolo did not employ dedicated local memory and relied on the bandwidth of the ARM core for DSP operand retrieval, impacting concurrent performance.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Piccolo's distinct instruction set also proved not to be a "good compiler target".
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Introduced in the ARMv6 architecture, this was a precursor to Advanced SIMD, also named Neon.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Jazelle DBX (Direct Bytecode eXecution) is a technique that allows Java bytecode to be executed directly in the ARM architecture as a third execution state (and instruction set) alongside the existing ARM and Thumb-mode.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Support for this state is signified by the "J" in the ARMv5TEJ architecture, and in ARM9EJ-S and ARM7EJ-S core names.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Support for this state is required starting in ARMv6 (except for the ARMv7-M profile), though newer cores only include a trivial implementation that provides no hardware acceleration.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] To improve compiled code density, processors since the ARM7TDMI (released in 1994) have featured the *Thumb* compressed instruction set, which have their own state.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] (The "T" in "TDMI" indicates the Thumb feature.) When in this state, the processor executes the Thumb instruction set, a compact 16-bit encoding for a subset of the ARM instruction set.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Most of the Thumb instructions are directly mapped to normal ARM instructions.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] The space saving comes from making some of the instruction operands implicit and limiting the number of possibilities compared to the ARM instructions executed in the ARM instruction set state.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] In Thumb, the 16-bit opcodes have less functionality.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] For example, only branches can be conditional, and many opcodes are restricted to accessing only half of all of the CPU's general-purpose registers.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] The shorter opcodes give improved code density overall, even though some operations require extra instructions.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] In situations where the memory port or bus width is constrained to less than 32 bits, the shorter Thumb opcodes allow increased performance compared with 32-bit ARM code, as less program code may need to be loaded into the processor over the constrained memory bandwidth.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Unlike processor architectures with variable length (16- or 32-bit) instructions, such as the Cray-1 and Hitachi SuperH, the ARM and Thumb instruction sets exist independently of each other.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Embedded hardware, such as the Game Boy Advance, typically have a small amount of RAM accessible with a full 32-bit datapath; the majority is accessed via a 16-bit or narrower secondary datapath.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] In this situation, it usually makes sense to compile Thumb code and hand-optimise a few of the most CPU-intensive sections using full 32-bit ARM instructions, placing these wider instructions into the 32-bit bus accessible memory.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] The first processor with a Thumb instruction decoder was the ARM7TDMI.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] All processors supporting 32-bit instruction sets, starting with ARM9, and including XScale, have included a Thumb instruction decoder.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] It includes instructions adopted from the Hitachi SuperH (1992), which was licensed by ARM.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] ARM's smallest processor families (Cortex M0 and M1) implement only the 16-bit Thumb instruction set for maximum performance in lowest cost applications.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] ARM processors that don't support 32-bit addressing also omit Thumb.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Thumb-2 extends the Thumb instruction set with bit-field manipulation, table branches and conditional execution.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] At the same time, the ARM instruction set was extended to maintain equivalent functionality in both instruction sets.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] A new "Unified Assembly Language" (UAL) supports generation of either Thumb or ARM instructions from the same source code; versions of Thumb seen on ARMv7 processors are essentially as capable as ARM code (including the ability to write interrupt handlers).
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] This requires a bit of care, and use of a new "IT" (if-then) instruction, which permits up to four successive instructions to execute based on a tested condition, or on its inverse.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] When compiling into ARM code, this is ignored, but when compiling into Thumb it generates an actual instruction.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] All ARMv7 chips support the Thumb instruction set.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] All chips in the Cortex-A series that support ARMv7, all Cortex-R series, and all ARM11 series support both "ARM instruction set state" and "Thumb instruction set state", while chips in the Cortex-M series support only the Thumb instruction set.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] New features provided by ThumbEE include automatic null pointer checks on every load and store instruction, an instruction to perform an array bounds check, and special instructions that call a handler.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] In addition, because it utilises Thumb-2 technology, ThumbEE provides access to registers r8–r15 (where the Jazelle/DBX Java VM state is held).
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Handlers are small sections of frequently called code, commonly used to implement high level languages, such as allocating memory for a new object.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] These changes come from repurposing a handful of opcodes, and knowing the core is in the new ThumbEE state.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] On 23 November 2011, Arm deprecated any use of the ThumbEE instruction set, and Armv8 removes support for ThumbEE.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Some devices such as the ARM Cortex-A8 have a cut-down *VFPLite* module instead of a full VFP module, and require roughly ten times more clock cycles per float operation.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Pre-Armv8 architecture implemented floating-point/SIMD with the coprocessor interface.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Other floating-point and/or SIMD units found in ARM-based processors using the coprocessor interface include FPA, FPE, iwMMXt, some of which were implemented in software by trapping but could have been implemented in hardware.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] They provide some of the same functionality as VFP but are not opcode-compatible with it.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] FPA10 also provides extended precision, but implements correct rounding (required by IEEE 754) only in single precision.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] An optional extension to the ARM instruction set in the ARMv5TE, ARMv5TEJ and ARMv6 architectures.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Implemented on most Cortex-A8 and A9 ARMv7 processors.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] It is backward-compatible with VFPv2, except that it cannot trap floating-point exceptions.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] VFPv3 has 32 64-bit FPU registers as standard, adds VCVT instructions to convert between scalar, float and double, adds immediate mode to VMOV such that constants can be loaded into FPU registers.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] As above, but with only 16 64-bit FPU registers.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Implemented on Cortex-A12 and A15 ARMv7 processors, Cortex-A7 optionally has VFPv4-D32 in the case of an FPU with Neon.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] As above, but it has only 16 64-bit FPU registers.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Implemented on Cortex-A5 and A7 processors in the case of an FPU without Neon.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Implemented on Cortex-M7 when single and double-precision floating-point core option exists.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] In Debian Linux and derivatives such as Ubuntu and Linux Mint, **armhf** (**ARM hard float**) refers to the ARMv7 architecture including the additional VFP3-D16 floating-point hardware extension (and Thumb-2) above.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Software packages and cross-compiler tools use the armhf vs. arm/armel suffixes to differentiate.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] The *Advanced SIMD* extension (also known as *Neon* or "MPE" Media Processing Engine) is a combined 64- and 128-bit SIMD instruction set that provides standardised acceleration for media and signal processing applications.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Neon is included in all Cortex-A8 devices, but is optional in Cortex-A9 devices.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Neon can execute MP3 audio decoding on CPUs running at 10 MHz, and can run the GSM adaptive multi-rate (AMR) speech codec at 13 MHz.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] It features a comprehensive instruction set, separate register files, and independent execution hardware.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Neon supports 8-, 16-, 32-, and 64-bit integer and single-precision (32-bit) floating-point data and SIMD operations for handling audio and video processing as well as graphics and gaming processing.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] In Neon, the SIMD supports up to 16 operations at the same time.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Neon hardware shares the same floating-point registers as used in VFP.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Devices such as the ARM Cortex-A8 and Cortex-A9 support 128-bit vectors, but will execute with 64 bits at a time, whereas some more powerful CPUs such as Cortex-A15 can execute 128 bits at a time.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] A quirk of Neon in Armv7 devices is that it flushes all subnormal numbers to zero, and as a result the GCC compiler will not use it unless `-funsafe-math-optimizations`, which allows losing denormals, is turned on.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] "Enhanced" Neon defined since Armv8 does not have this quirk, but as of GCC 8.2 the same flag is still required to enable Neon instructions.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] On the other hand, GCC does consider Neon safe on AArch64 for Armv8.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] ProjectNe10 is ARM's first open-source project (from its inception; while they acquired an older project, now named Mbed TLS).
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Ne10 library is a set of common, useful functions written in both Neon and C (for compatibility).
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] The library was created to allow developers to use Neon optimisations without learning Neon, but it also serves as a set of highly optimised Neon intrinsic and assembly code examples for common DSP, arithmetic, and image processing routines.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Helium is the M-Profile Vector Extension (MVE).
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] It adds more than 150 scalar and vector instructions.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Security Extensions, marketed as TrustZone Technology, is in ARMv6KZ and later application profile architectures.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] It provides a low-cost alternative to adding another dedicated security core to an SoC, by providing two virtual processors backed by hardware based access control.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] This lets the application core switch between two states, referred to as *worlds* (to reduce confusion with other names for capability domains), to prevent information leaking from the more trusted world (the *Secure world*) to the less trusted world (the *Normal world*).
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] This world switch is generally orthogonal to all other capabilities of the processor, thus each world can operate independently of the other while using the same core.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Memory and peripherals are then made aware of the operating world of the core and may use this to provide access control to secrets and code on the device.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Typically, a rich operating system is run in the less trusted world, with smaller security-specialised code in the more trusted world, aiming to reduce the attack surface.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Typical applications include DRM functionality for controlling the use of media on ARM-based devices, and preventing any unapproved use of the device.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] In practice, since the specific implementation details of proprietary TrustZone implementations have not been publicly disclosed for review, it is unclear what level of assurance is provided for a given threat model, but they are not immune from attack.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Open Virtualization is an open source implementation of the trusted world architecture for TrustZone.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] AMD has licensed and incorporated TrustZone technology into its Secure Processor Technology.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] AMD's APUs include a Cortex-A5 processor for handling secure processing, which is enabled in some, but not all products.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] In fact, the Cortex-A5 TrustZone core had been included in earlier AMD products, but was not enabled due to time constraints.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Samsung Knox uses TrustZone for purposes such as detecting modifications to the kernel, storing certificates and attestating keys.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Security Extension, marketed as TrustZone for Armv8-M Technology, was introduced in the Armv8-M architecture.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] While containing similar concepts to TrustZone for Armv8-A, it has a different architectural design, as world switching is performed using branch instructions instead of using exceptions.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] It also supports safe interleaved interrupt handling from either world regardless of the current security state.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Together these features provide low latency calls to the secure world and responsive interrupt handling.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] ARM provides a reference stack of secure world code in the form of Trusted Firmware for M and PSA Certified.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] As of ARMv6, the ARM architecture supports no-execute page protection, which is referred to as *XN*, for *eXecute Never*.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Large Physical Address Extension (LPAE), which extends the physical address size from 32 bits to 40 bits, was added to the Armv7-A architecture in 2011.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] The physical address size may be even larger in processors based on the 64-bit (Armv8-A) architecture.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] For example, it is 44 bits in Cortex-A75 and Cortex-A65AE.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] The **Armv8-R** and **Armv8-M** architectures, announced after the Armv8-A architecture, share some features with Armv8-A.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] However, Armv8-M does not include any 64-bit AArch64 instructions, and Armv8-R originally did not include any AArch64 instructions; those instructions were added to Armv8-R later.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Armv8.1-M architecture, announced in February 2019, is an enhancement of the Armv8-M architecture.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Announced in October 2011, **Armv8-A** (often called ARMv8 while the Armv8-R is also available) represents a fundamental change to the ARM architecture.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] It supports two *Execution states*: a 64-bit state named *AArch64* and a 32-bit state named *AArch32*.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] In the AArch64 state, a new 64-bit *A64* instruction set is supported; in the AArch32 state, two instruction sets are supported: the original 32-bit instruction set, named *A32*, and the 32-bit Thumb-2 instruction set, named *T32*.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] AArch32 provides user-space compatibility with Armv7-A.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] The processor state can change on an Exception level change; this allows 32-bit applications to be executed in AArch32 state under a 64-bit OS whose kernel executes in AArch64 state, and allows a 32-bit OS to run in AArch32 state under the control of a 64-bit hypervisor running in AArch64 state.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] ARM announced their Cortex-A53 and Cortex-A57 cores on 30 October 2012.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Apple was the first to release an Armv8-A compatible core in a consumer product (Apple A7 in iPhone 5S).
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] AppliedMicro, using an FPGA, was the first to demo Armv8-A.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] The first Armv8-A SoC from Samsung is the Exynos 5433 used in the Galaxy Note 4, which features two clusters of four Cortex-A57 and Cortex-A53 cores in a big.LITTLE configuration; but it will run only in AArch32 mode.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] To both AArch32 and AArch64, Armv8-A makes VFPv3/v4 and advanced SIMD (Neon) standard.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] It also adds cryptography instructions supporting AES, SHA-1/SHA-256 and finite field arithmetic.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] AArch64 was introduced in Armv8-A and its subsequent revision.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] AArch64 is not included in the 32-bit Armv8-R and Armv8-M architectures.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] An ARMv8-A processor can support one or both of AArch32 and AArch64; it may support AArch32 and AArch64 at lower Exception levels and only AArch64 at higher Exception levels.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] For example, the ARM Cortex-A32 supports only AArch32, the ARM Cortex-A34 supports only AArch64, and the ARM Cortex-A72 supports both AArch64 and AArch32.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] An ARMv9-A processor must support AArch64 at all Exception levels, and may support AArch32 at EL0.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Optional AArch64 support was added to the Armv8-R profile, with the first ARM core implementing it being the Cortex-R82.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Announced in March 2021, the updated architecture places a focus on secure execution and compartmentalisation.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] The first ARMv9-A processors were released later that year, including the Cortex-A510, Cortex-A710 and Cortex-X2.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Arm SystemReady is a compliance program that helps ensure the interoperability of an operating system on Arm-based hardware from datacenter servers to industrial edge and IoT devices.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] The key building blocks of the program are the specifications for minimum hardware and firmware requirements that the operating systems and hypervisors can rely upon.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] These specifications are co-developed by Arm and its partners in the System Architecture Advisory Committee (SystemArchAC).
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Architecture Compliance Suite (ACS) is the test tools that help to check the compliance of these specifications.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Arm SystemReady Requirements Specification documents the requirements of the certifications.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] This program was introduced by Arm in 2020 at the first DevSummit event.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Its predecessor Arm ServerReady was introduced in 2018 at the Arm TechCon event.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] PSA Certified, formerly named Platform Security Architecture, is an architecture-agnostic security framework and evaluation scheme.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] It is intended to help secure Internet of things (IoT) devices built on system-on-a-chip (SoC) processors.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] It was introduced to increase security where a full trusted execution environment is too large or complex.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] The architecture was introduced by Arm in 2017 at the annual TechCon event.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Although the scheme is architecture agnostic, it was first implemented on Arm Cortex-M processor cores intended for microcontroller use.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] PSA Certified includes freely available threat models and security analyses that demonstrate the process for deciding on security features in common IoT products.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] It also provides freely downloadable application programming interface (API) packages, architectural specifications, open-source firmware implementations, and related test suites.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Following the development of the architecture security framework in 2017, the PSA Certified assurance scheme launched two years later at Embedded World in 2019.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] PSA Certified offers a multi-level security evaluation scheme for chip vendors, OS providers and IoT device makers.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Embedded World presentation introduced chip vendors to Level 1 Certification.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] A draft of Level 2 protection was presented at the same time.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Level 2 certification became a usable standard in February 2020.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] The certification was created by PSA Joint Stakeholders to enable a security-by-design approach for a diverse set of IoT products.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] PSA Certified specifications are implementation and architecture agnostic, as a result they can be applied to any chip, software or device.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] The certification also removes industry fragmentation for IoT product manufacturers and developers.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] The first 32-bit ARM-based personal computer, the Acorn Archimedes, was originally intended to run an ambitious operating system called ARX.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] The machines shipped with RISC OS, which was also used on later ARM-based systems from Acorn and other vendors.
[src:pointer-authentication/arm-architecture-family-p02] Some early Acorn machines were also able to run a Unix port called RISC iX.
[src:pointer-authentication/control-flow-integrity] A computer program commonly changes its control flow to make decisions and use different parts of the code.
[src:pointer-authentication/control-flow-integrity] Such transfers may be *direct*, in that the target address is written in the code itself, or *indirect*, in that the target address itself is a variable in memory or a CPU register.
[src:pointer-authentication/control-flow-integrity] In a typical function call, the program performs a direct call, but returns to the caller function using the stack – an indirect *backward-edge* transfer.
[src:pointer-authentication/control-flow-integrity] When a function pointer is called, such as from a virtual table, we say there is an indirect *forward-edge* transfer.
[src:pointer-authentication/control-flow-integrity] Attackers seek to inject code into a program to make use of its privileges or to extract data from its memory space.
[src:pointer-authentication/control-flow-integrity] Before executable code was commonly made read-only, an attacker could arbitrarily change the code as it is run, targeting direct transfers or even do with no transfers at all.
[src:pointer-authentication/control-flow-integrity] CFI is designed to protect indirect transfers from going to unintended locations.
[src:pointer-authentication/control-flow-integrity] Associated techniques include code-pointer separation (CPS), code-pointer integrity (CPI), stack canaries, shadow stacks (SS), and vtable pointer verification.
[src:pointer-authentication/control-flow-integrity] These protections can be classified into either *coarse-grained* or *fine-grained* based on the number of targets restricted.
[src:pointer-authentication/control-flow-integrity] Related implementations are available in Clang (LLVM front-end),, GNU Compiler Collection, Microsoft's Control Flow Guard and Return Flow Guard, Google's Indirect Function-Call Checks and Reuse Attack Protector (RAP).
[src:pointer-authentication/control-flow-integrity] The LLVM compiler's C/C++ front-end Clang provides a number of "CFI" schemes that works on the forward edge by checking for errors in virtual tables and type casts.
[src:pointer-authentication/control-flow-integrity] Not all of the schemes are supported on all platforms and most of them, the exception being two "kcfi" schemes intended for low-level kernel software, depends on link-time optimization (LTO) to know what functions are supposed to be called in normal cases.
[src:pointer-authentication/control-flow-integrity] Also provided is a separate "shadow call stack" (SCS) instrumentation pass that defends on the backward edge by checking for call stack modifications, available only for the aarch64 and RISC-V ISAs.
[src:pointer-authentication/control-flow-integrity] And due to use of a shared processor register SCS is only enforceable on certain ABIs or if in other ways it is ensured that any other software using the register set (thread/processor) does not interfere with this use.
[src:pointer-authentication/control-flow-integrity] Google has shipped Android with the Linux kernel compiled by Clang with link-time optimization (LTO) and CFI enabled since 2018.
[src:pointer-authentication/control-flow-integrity] Even though SCS is available for the Linux kernel as an option, and support is also available for Android's system components it is recommended only to enable it for components for which it can be ensured that no third party code is loaded.
[src:pointer-authentication/control-flow-integrity] The GNU Compiler Collection implemented a "shadow call stack" compatible with Clang for aarch64 in v12 released in 2022.
[src:pointer-authentication/control-flow-integrity] This feature is primarily intended for building the Linux kernel as support is missing from GCC user space libraries.
[src:pointer-authentication/control-flow-integrity] Intel Control-flow Enforcement Technology (CET) detects compromises to control flow integrity with a shadow stack (SS) and indirect branch tracking (IBT).
[src:pointer-authentication/control-flow-integrity] The kernel must map a region of memory for the shadow stack not writable to user space programs except by special instructions.
[src:pointer-authentication/control-flow-integrity] The shadow stack stores a copy of the return address of each CALL.
[src:pointer-authentication/control-flow-integrity] On a RET, the processor checks if the return address stored in the normal stack and shadow stack are equal.
[src:pointer-authentication/control-flow-integrity] If the addresses are not equal, the processor generates an INT #21 (Control Flow Protection Fault).
[src:pointer-authentication/control-flow-integrity] Indirect branch tracking detects indirect JMP or CALL instructions to unauthorized targets.
[src:pointer-authentication/control-flow-integrity] It is implemented by adding a new internal state machine in the processor.
[src:pointer-authentication/control-flow-integrity] The behavior of indirect JMP and CALL instructions is changed so that they switch the state machine from IDLE to WAIT_FOR_ENDBRANCH.
[src:pointer-authentication/control-flow-integrity] In the WAIT_FOR_ENDBRANCH state, the next instruction to be executed is required to be the new ENDBRANCH instruction (ENDBR32 in 32-bit mode or ENDBR64 in 64-bit mode), which changes the internal state machine from WAIT_FOR_ENDBRANCH back to IDLE.
[src:pointer-authentication/control-flow-integrity] Thus every authorized target of an indirect JMP or CALL must begin with ENDBRANCH.
[src:pointer-authentication/control-flow-integrity] If the processor is in a WAIT_FOR_ENDBRANCH state (meaning, the previous instruction was an indirect JMP or CALL), and the next instruction is not an ENDBRANCH instruction, the processor generates an INT #21 (Control Flow Protection Fault).
[src:pointer-authentication/control-flow-integrity] On processors not supporting CET indirect branch tracking, ENDBRANCH instructions are interpreted as NOPs and have no effect.
[src:pointer-authentication/control-flow-integrity] Control Flow Guard (CFG) was first released for Windows 8.1 Update 3 (KB3000850) in November 2014.
[src:pointer-authentication/control-flow-integrity] Developers can add CFG to their programs by adding the `/guard:cf` linker flag before program linking in Visual Studio 2015 or newer.
[src:pointer-authentication/control-flow-integrity] As of Windows 10 Creators Update (Windows 10 version 1703), the Windows kernel is compiled with CFG.
[src:pointer-authentication/control-flow-integrity] The Windows kernel uses Hyper-V to prevent malicious kernel code from overwriting the CFG bitmap.
[src:pointer-authentication/control-flow-integrity] CFG operates by creating a per-process bitmap, where a set bit indicates that the address is a valid destination.
[src:pointer-authentication/control-flow-integrity] Before performing each indirect function call, the application checks if the destination address is in the bitmap.
[src:pointer-authentication/control-flow-integrity] If the destination address is not in the bitmap, the program terminates.
[src:pointer-authentication/control-flow-integrity] This makes it more difficult for an attacker to exploit a use-after-free by replacing an object's contents and then using an indirect function call to execute a payload.
[src:pointer-authentication/control-flow-integrity] The first four bits are the 4th through 8th low-order bits of the address.
[src:pointer-authentication/control-flow-integrity] The 5th bit of the bit offset is set to 0 if the destination address is aligned with 0x10 (last four bits are 0), and 1 if it is not.
[src:pointer-authentication/control-flow-integrity] If the target address is not in the bitmap, terminate the program.
[src:pointer-authentication/control-flow-integrity] eXtended Flow Guard (XFG) has not been officially released yet, but is available in the Windows Insider preview and was publicly presented at Bluehat Shanghai in 2019.
[src:pointer-authentication/control-flow-integrity] XFG extends CFG by validating function call signatures to ensure that indirect function calls are only to the subset of functions with the same signature.
[src:pointer-authentication/control-flow-integrity] Function call signature validation is implemented by adding instructions to store the target function's hash in register r10 immediately prior to the indirect call and storing the calculated function hash in the memory immediately preceding the target address's code.
[src:pointer-authentication/control-flow-integrity] When the indirect call is made, the XFG validation function compares the value in r10 to the target function's stored hash.
[src:pointer-authentication/message-authentication-code] In cryptography, a **message authentication code** (**MAC**), sometimes known as an **authentication tag**, is a short piece of information used for authenticating and integrity-checking a message.
[src:pointer-authentication/message-authentication-code] In other words, it is used to confirm that the message came from the stated sender (its authenticity) and has not been changed (its integrity).
[src:pointer-authentication/message-authentication-code] The MAC value allows verifiers (who also possess a secret key) to detect any changes to the message content.
[src:pointer-authentication/message-authentication-code] The term **message integrity code** (**MIC**) is frequently substituted for the term *MAC*, especially in communications to distinguish it from the use of the latter as *Media Access Control* (as in *MAC address*).
[src:pointer-authentication/message-authentication-code] However, some authors use MIC to refer to a message digest, which aims only to uniquely but opaquely identify a single message.
[src:pointer-authentication/message-authentication-code] As such, it is recommended to avoid the term *message integrity code* (MIC), and instead use *checksum*, *error detection code*, *hash*, **keyed hash**, *message authentication code*, or *protected checksum*.
[src:pointer-authentication/message-authentication-code] A secure message authentication code must resist attempts by an adversary to forge tags, for arbitrary, selected, or all messages, including under conditions of known- or chosen-message.
[src:pointer-authentication/message-authentication-code] It should be computationally infeasible to compute a valid tag of the given message without knowledge of the key, even if for the worst case, we assume the adversary knows the tag of any message but the one in question.
[src:pointer-authentication/message-authentication-code] where *A**S*(*k*, · ) denotes that *A* has access to the oracle *S*(*k*, · ), and Query(*A**S*(*k*, · ), 1*n*) denotes the set of the queries on *S* made by *A*, which knows *n*.
[src:pointer-authentication/message-authentication-code] Clearly we require that any adversary cannot directly query the string *x* on *S*, since otherwise a valid tag can be easily obtained by that adversary.
[src:pointer-authentication/message-authentication-code] While MAC functions are similar to cryptographic hash functions, they possess different security requirements.
[src:pointer-authentication/message-authentication-code] To be considered secure, a MAC function must resist existential forgery under chosen-message attacks.
[src:pointer-authentication/message-authentication-code] This means that even if an attacker has access to an oracle which possesses the secret key and generates MACs for messages of the attacker's choosing, the attacker cannot guess the MAC for other messages (which were not used to query the oracle) without performing infeasible amounts of computation.
[src:pointer-authentication/message-authentication-code] MACs differ from digital signatures as MAC values are both generated and verified using the same secret key.
[src:pointer-authentication/message-authentication-code] This implies that the sender and receiver of a message must agree on the same key before initiating communications, as is the case with symmetric encryption.
[src:pointer-authentication/message-authentication-code] For the same reason, MACs do not provide the property of non-repudiation offered by signatures specifically in the case of a network-wide shared secret key: any user who can verify a MAC is also capable of generating MACs for other messages.
[src:pointer-authentication/message-authentication-code] In contrast, a digital signature is generated using the private key of a key pair, which is public-key cryptography.
[src:pointer-authentication/message-authentication-code] Since this private key is only accessible to its holder, a digital signature proves that a document was signed by none other than that holder.
[src:pointer-authentication/message-authentication-code] Thus, digital signatures do offer non-repudiation.
[src:pointer-authentication/message-authentication-code] This is commonly done in the finance industry.
[src:pointer-authentication/message-authentication-code] While the primary goal of a MAC is to prevent forgery by adversaries without knowledge of the secret key, this is insufficient in certain scenarios.
[src:pointer-authentication/message-authentication-code] When an adversary is able to control the MAC key, stronger guarantees are needed, akin to collision resistance or preimage security in hash functions.
[src:pointer-authentication/message-authentication-code] For MACs, these concepts are known as *commitment* and *context-discovery* security.
[src:pointer-authentication/message-authentication-code] MAC algorithms can be constructed from other cryptographic primitives, like cryptographic hash functions (as in the case of HMAC) or from block cipher algorithms (OMAC, CCM, GCM, and PMAC).
[src:pointer-authentication/message-authentication-code] However many of the fastest MAC algorithms, like UMAC-VMAC and Poly1305-AES, are constructed based on universal hashing.
[src:pointer-authentication/message-authentication-code] Intrinsically keyed hash algorithms such as SipHash are also by definition MACs; they can be even faster than universal-hashing based MACs.
[src:pointer-authentication/message-authentication-code] Additionally, the MAC algorithm can deliberately combine two or more cryptographic primitives, so as to maintain protection even if one of them is later found to be vulnerable.
[src:pointer-authentication/message-authentication-code] For instance, in Transport Layer Security (TLS) versions before 1.2, the input data is split in halves that are each processed with a different hashing primitive (SHA-1 and SHA-2) then XORed together to output the MAC.
[src:pointer-authentication/message-authentication-code] Universal hashing and in particular pairwise independent hash functions provide a secure message authentication code as long as the key is used at most once.
[src:pointer-authentication/message-authentication-code] This can be seen as the one-time pad for authentication.
[src:pointer-authentication/message-authentication-code] The simplest such pairwise independent hash function is defined by the random key, *key* = (*a*, *b*), and the MAC tag for a message *m* is computed as *tag* = (*am* + *b*) mod *p*, where *p* is prime.
[src:pointer-authentication/message-authentication-code] More generally, *k*-independent hashing functions provide a secure message authentication code as long as the key is used less than *k* times for *k*-ways independent hashing functions.
[src:pointer-authentication/message-authentication-code] Message authentication codes and data origin authentication have been also discussed in the framework of quantum cryptography.
[src:pointer-authentication/message-authentication-code] By contrast to other cryptographic tasks, such as key distribution, for a rather broad class of quantum MACs it has been shown that quantum resources do not offer any advantage over unconditionally secure one-time classical MACs.
[src:pointer-authentication/message-authentication-code] Various standards exist that define MAC algorithms.
[src:pointer-authentication/message-authentication-code] ISO/IEC 9797-1 and -2 define generic models and algorithms that can be used with any block cipher or hash function, and a variety of different parameters.
[src:pointer-authentication/message-authentication-code] These models and parameters allow more specific algorithms to be defined by nominating the parameters.
[src:pointer-authentication/message-authentication-code] For example, the FIPS PUB 113 algorithm is functionally equivalent to ISO/IEC 9797-1 MAC algorithm 1 with padding method 1 and a block cipher algorithm of DES.
[src:pointer-authentication/message-authentication-code] In this example, the sender of a message runs it through a MAC algorithm to produce a MAC data tag.
[src:pointer-authentication/message-authentication-code] The message and the MAC tag are then sent to the receiver.
[src:pointer-authentication/message-authentication-code] The receiver in turn runs the message portion of the transmission through the same MAC algorithm using the same key, producing a second MAC data tag.
[src:pointer-authentication/message-authentication-code] The receiver then compares the first MAC tag received in the transmission to the second generated MAC tag.
[src:pointer-authentication/message-authentication-code] If they are identical, the receiver can safely assume that the message was not altered or tampered with during transmission (data integrity).
[src:pointer-authentication/message-authentication-code] However, to allow the receiver to be able to detect replay attacks, the message itself must contain data that assures that this same message can only be sent once (e.g. time stamp, sequence number or use of a one-time MAC).
[src:pointer-authentication/message-authentication-code] Otherwise an attacker could – without even understanding its content – record this message and play it back at a later time, producing the same result as the original sender.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In computer science, a **pointer** is an object in many programming languages that stores a memory address.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] This can be that of another value located in computer memory, or in some cases, that of memory-mapped computer hardware.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] A pointer *references* a location in memory, and obtaining the value stored at that location is known as *dereferencing* the pointer.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] As an analogy, a page number in a book's index could be considered a pointer to the corresponding page; dereferencing such a pointer would be done by flipping to the page with the given page number and reading the text found on that page.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The actual format and content of a pointer variable is dependent on the underlying computer architecture.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Using pointers significantly improves performance for repetitive operations, like traversing iterable data structures (e.g. strings, lookup tables, control tables, linked lists, and tree structures).
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In particular, it is often much cheaper in time and space to copy and dereference pointers than it is to copy and access the data to which the pointers point.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Pointers are also used to hold the addresses of entry points for called subroutines in procedural programming and for run-time linking to dynamic link libraries (DLLs).
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In object-oriented programming, pointers to functions are used for binding methods, often using virtual method tables.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] A pointer is a simple, more concrete implementation of the more abstract *reference* data type.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Several languages, especially low-level languages, support some type of pointer, although some have more restrictions on their use than others.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Because pointers allow both protected and unprotected access to memory addresses, there are risks associated with using them, particularly in the latter case.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Primitive pointers are often stored in a format similar to an integer; however, attempting to dereference or "look up" such a pointer whose value is not a valid memory address could cause a program to crash (or contain invalid data).
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] To alleviate this potential problem, as a matter of type safety, pointers are considered a separate type parameterized by the type of data they point to, even if the underlying representation is an integer.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Other measures may also be taken (such as validation and bounds checking), to verify that the pointer variable contains a value that is both a valid memory address and within the numerical range that the processor is capable of addressing.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In 1955, Soviet Ukrainian computer scientist Kateryna Yushchenko created the Address programming language that made possible indirect addressing and addresses of the highest rank – analogous to pointers.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] This language was widely used on the Soviet computers.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] However, it was unknown outside the Soviet Union and usually Harold Lawson is credited with the invention, in 1964, of the pointer.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In 2000, Lawson was presented the Computer Pioneer Award by the IEEE "[f]or inventing the pointer variable and introducing this concept into PL/I, thus providing for the first time, the capability to flexibly treat linked lists in a general-purpose high-level language".
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] His seminal paper on the concepts appeared in the June 1967 issue of CACM entitled: PL/I List Processing.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] According to the Oxford English Dictionary, the **word** *pointer* first appeared in print as a *stack pointer* in a technical memorandum by the System Development Corporation.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In computer science, a pointer is a kind of reference.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] A *data primitive* (or just *primitive*) is any datum that can be read from or written to computer memory using one memory access (for instance, both a *byte* and a *word* are primitives).
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] A *data aggregate* (or just *aggregate*) is a group of primitives that are logically contiguous in memory and that are viewed collectively as one datum (for instance, an aggregate could be 3 logically contiguous bytes, the values of which represent the 3 coordinates of a point in space).
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] When an aggregate is entirely composed of the same type of primitive, the aggregate may be called an *array*; in a sense, a multi-byte *word* primitive is an array of bytes, and some programs use words in this way.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In the context of these definitions, a *byte* is the smallest primitive; each memory address specifies a different byte.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The memory address of the initial byte of a datum is considered the memory address (or *base memory address*) of the entire datum.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] A *memory pointer* (or just *pointer*) is a primitive, the value of which is intended to be used as a memory address; it is said that *a pointer points to a memory address*.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] It is also said that *a pointer points to a datum [in memory]* when the pointer's value is the datum's memory address.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] More generally, a pointer is a kind of reference, and it is said that *a pointer references a datum stored somewhere in memory*; to obtain that datum is *to dereference the pointer*.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The feature that separates pointers from other kinds of reference is that a pointer's value is meant to be interpreted as a memory address, which is a rather low-level concept.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] References serve as a level of indirection: A pointer's value determines which memory address (that is, which datum) is to be used in a calculation.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Because indirection is a fundamental aspect of algorithms, pointers are often expressed as a fundamental data type in programming languages; in statically (or strongly) typed programming languages, the type of a pointer determines the type of the datum to which the pointer points.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Pointers are a very thin abstraction on top of the addressing capabilities provided by most modern architectures.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The system would then also provide an operation to retrieve the value stored in the memory unit at a given address (usually utilizing the machine's general-purpose registers).
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In the usual case, a pointer is large enough to hold more addresses than there are units of memory in the system.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] This introduces the possibility that a program may attempt to access an address which corresponds to no unit of memory, either because not enough memory is installed (i.e. beyond the range of available memory) or the architecture does not support such addresses.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The first case may, in certain platforms such as the Intel x86 architecture, be called a segmentation fault (segfault).
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The second case is possible in the current implementation of AMD64, where pointers are 64 bit long and addresses only extend to 48 bits.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Pointers must conform to certain rules (canonical addresses), so if a non-canonical pointer is dereferenced, the processor raises a general protection fault.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] On the other hand, some systems have more units of memory than there are addresses.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In this case, a more complex scheme such as memory segmentation or paging is employed to use different parts of the memory at different times.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The last incarnations of the x86 architecture support up to 36 bits of physical memory addresses, which were mapped to the 32-bit linear address space through the PAE paging mechanism.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Thus, only 1/16 of the possible total memory may be accessed at a time.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In order to provide a consistent interface, some architectures provide memory-mapped I/O, which allows some addresses to refer to units of memory while others refer to device registers of other devices in the computer.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] There are analogous concepts such as file offsets, array indices, and remote object references that serve some of the same purposes as addresses for other types of objects.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Pointers are directly supported without restrictions in languages such as PL/I, C, C++, Pascal, FreeBASIC, and implicitly in most assembly languages.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] They are used mainly to construct references, which in turn are fundamental to construct nearly all data structures, and to pass data between different parts of a program.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In functional programming languages that rely heavily on lists, data references are managed abstractly by using primitive constructs like cons and the corresponding elements car and cdr, which can be thought of as specialised pointers to the first and second components of a cons-cell.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] This gives rise to some of the idiomatic "flavour" of functional programming.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] By structuring data in such cons-lists, these languages facilitate recursive means for building and processing data—for example, by recursively accessing the head and tail elements of lists of lists; e.g.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] By contrast, memory management based on pointer dereferencing in some approximation of an array of memory addresses facilitates treating variables as slots into which data can be assigned imperatively.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] When dealing with arrays, the critical lookup operation typically involves a stage called *address calculation* which involves constructing a pointer to the desired data element in the array.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In other data structures, such as linked lists, pointers are used as references to explicitly tie one piece of the structure to another.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Pointers are used to pass parameters by reference.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] This is useful if the programmer wants a function's modifications to a parameter to be visible to the function's caller.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] This is also useful for returning multiple values from a function.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Pointers can also be used to allocate and deallocate dynamic variables and arrays in memory.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Since a variable will often become redundant after it has served its purpose, it is a waste of memory to keep it, and therefore it is good practice to deallocate it (using the original pointer reference) when it is no longer needed.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Failure to do so may result in a *memory leak* (where available free memory gradually, or in severe cases rapidly, diminishes because of an accumulation of numerous redundant memory blocks).
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] This declares a variable `ptr` that stores a pointer to an object of type `int`.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Other types can be used in place of `int`; for example, `bool *ptr` would declare a pointer to an object of type `bool`.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] After a pointer has been declared, it can be assigned an address.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Both `int *x, y;` and `int* x, y;` declare `x` to be a pointer to `int`, but declare `y` to be an `int`.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] This is because the `*` applies only to the variable immediately following it.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The asterisk can also be used on the left-hand side of an assignment to change the object `a` without having to be in the same scope.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] If `a` is accessed later, its new value will be 8.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Because the C language does not specify an implicit initialization for objects of automatic storage duration, pointer variables can sometimes point to unexpected locations, causing undefined behavior.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] To combat this, pointers are sometimes initialized with a null pointer value, represented in C by the `NULL` macro; in C23 and later, `nullptr` is also available as an alternative, which is of type `nullptr_t`.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Dereferencing a null pointer produces undefined behavior, which can result in unpredictable bugs and results.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] This example may be clearer if memory is examined directly.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Assume that `a` is located at address 0x8130 in memory and `ptr` at 0x8134; also assume this is a 32-bit machine such that an int is 32-bits wide.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Clearly, accessing `a` will yield the value of 8 because the previous instruction modified the contents of `a` by way of the pointer `ptr`.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] When setting up data structures like lists, queues and trees, it is necessary to have pointers to help manage how the structure is implemented and controlled.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Typical examples of pointers are start pointers, end pointers, and stack pointers.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Relative addresses are a form of manual memory segmentation, and share many of its advantages and disadvantages.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] A two-byte offset, containing a 16-bit, unsigned integer, can be used to provide relative addressing for up to 64 KiB (216 bytes) of a data structure.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Generally, though, such schemes are a lot of trouble, and for convenience to the programmer absolute addresses (and underlying that, a *flat address space*) is preferred.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] A one byte offset, such as the hexadecimal ASCII value of a character (e.g.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] X'29') can be used to point to an alternative integer value (or index) in an array (e.g., X'01').
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In this way, characters can be very efficiently translated from 'raw data' to a usable sequential index and then to an absolute address without a lookup table.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] This allocates a block of five integers and names the block `a`; the expression `a` evaluates, in most contexts, as a pointer to the first element of the block.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Another common use of pointers is to point to dynamically allocated memory from malloc which returns a consecutive block of memory of no less than the requested size that can be used as an array.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] While, when used as an operand for most operators, an array evaluates as a pointer to the first element of the array, this is not the case for the `sizeof` operator.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In this example, `sizeof(a)` will evaluate to `5 * sizeof(int)` (the size of the array), while `sizeof(ptr)` will evaluate to `sizeof(int *)`, the size of the pointer itself.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Represented here are five integers: 2, 4, 3, 1, and 5.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] These five integers occupy 32 bits (4 bytes) each with the least-significant byte stored first (this is a little-endian CPU architecture) and are stored consecutively starting at address 0x1000.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The last example is how to access the contents of `a`.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Below is an example definition of a linked list in C.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] where `Nil` is the empty list, and `Cons a (LinkedList a)` is a cons cell of type `a` with another link also of type `a`.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The definition with references, however, is type-checked and does not use potentially confusing signal values.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] For this reason, data structures in C are usually dealt with via wrapper functions, which are carefully checked for correctness.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Pointers can be used to pass variables by their address, allowing their value to be changed.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In some programs, the required amount of memory depends on what *the user* may enter.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In such cases the programmer needs to allocate memory dynamically.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] This is done by allocating memory at the *heap* rather than on the *stack*, where variables usually are stored (although variables can also be stored in the CPU registers).
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Dynamic memory allocation can only be made through pointers, and names – like with common variables – cannot be given.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Pointers are used to store and manage the addresses of dynamically allocated blocks of memory.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Such blocks are used to store data objects or arrays of objects.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Most structured and object-oriented languages provide an area of memory, called the *heap* or *free store*, from which objects are dynamically allocated.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The example C code below illustrates how structure objects are dynamically allocated and referenced.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The standard C library provides the function `malloc()` for allocating memory blocks from the heap.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] It takes the size of an object to allocate as a parameter and returns a pointer to a newly allocated block of memory suitable for storing the object, or it returns a null pointer if the allocation failed.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The code below illustrates how memory objects are dynamically deallocated, i.e., returned to the heap or free store.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The standard C library provides the function `free()` for deallocating a previously allocated memory block and returning it back to the heap.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] On some computing architectures, pointers can be used to directly manipulate memory or memory-mapped devices.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Assigning addresses to pointers is an invaluable tool when programming microcontrollers.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In the mid-1980s, using the BIOS to access the video capabilities of PCs was slow.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Applications that were display-intensive typically used to access CGA video memory directly by casting the hexadecimal constant 0xB8000 to a pointer to an array of 80 unsigned 16-bit int values.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Each value consisted of an ASCII code in the low byte, and a colour in the high byte.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Control tables that are used to control program flow usually make extensive use of pointers.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The pointers, usually embedded in a table entry, may, for instance, be used to hold the entry points to subroutines to be executed, based on certain conditions defined in the same table entry.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The pointers can however be simply indexes to other separate, but associated, tables comprising an array of the actual addresses or the addresses themselves (depending upon the programming language constructs available).
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] They can also be used to point to earlier table entries (as in loop processing) or forward to skip some table entries (as in a switch or "early" exit from a loop).
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] For this latter purpose, the "pointer" may simply be the table entry number itself and can be transformed into an actual address by simple arithmetic.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In many languages, pointers have the additional restriction that the object they point to has a specific type.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] For example, a pointer may be declared to point to an integer; the language will then attempt to prevent the programmer from pointing it to objects which are not integers, such as floating-point numbers, eliminating some errors.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] `money` would be an integer pointer and `bags` would be a char pointer.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] because `money` and `bags` were declared with different types.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] which says to cast the integer pointer of `money` to a char pointer and assign to `bags`.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] A 2005 draft of the C standard requires that casting a pointer derived from one type to one of another type should maintain the alignment correctness for both types (6.3.2.3 Pointers, par.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In languages that allow pointer arithmetic, arithmetic on pointers takes into account the size of the type.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] For example, adding an integer number to a pointer produces another pointer that points to an address that is higher by that number times the size of the type.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] This allows us to easily compute the address of elements of an array of a given type, as was shown in the C arrays example above.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] When a pointer of one type is cast to another type of a different size, the programmer should expect that pointer arithmetic will be calculated differently.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In C, for example, if the `money` array starts at 0x2000 and `sizeof(int)` is 4 bytes whereas `sizeof(char)` is 1 byte, then `money + 1` will point to 0x2004, but `bags + 1` would point to 0x2001.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Other risks of casting include loss of data when "wide" data is written to "narrow" locations (e.g.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] `bags[0] = 65537;`), unexpected results when bit-shifting values, and comparison problems, especially with signed vs unsigned values.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Although it is impossible in general to determine at compile-time which casts are safe, some languages store run-time type information which can be used to confirm that these dangerous casts are valid at runtime.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Other languages merely accept a conservative approximation of safe casts, or none at all.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In C and C++, even if two pointers compare as equal that doesn't mean they are equivalent.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In these languages *and* LLVM, the rule is interpreted to mean that "just because two pointers point to the same address, does not mean they are equal in the sense that they can be used interchangeably", the difference between the pointers referred to as their *provenance*.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Casting to an integer type such as `uintptr_t` is implementation-defined and the comparison it provides does not provide any more insight as to whether the two pointers are interchangeable.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In addition, further conversion to bytes and arithmetic will throw off optimizers trying to keep track the use of pointers, a problem still being elucidated in academic research.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] As a pointer allows a program to attempt to access an object that may not be defined, pointers can be the origin of a variety of programming errors.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] However, the usefulness of pointers is so great that it can be difficult to perform programming tasks without them.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Consequently, many languages have created constructs designed to provide some of the useful features of pointers without some of their pitfalls, also sometimes referred to as *pointer hazards*.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In this context, pointers that directly address memory (as used in this article) are referred to as **raw pointers** or **naked pointer**, by contrast with smart pointers or other variants.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] One major problem with pointers is that as long as they can be directly manipulated as a number, they can be made to point to unused addresses or to data which is being used for other purposes.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Array indexing is handled as a special case.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] A pointer which does not have any address assigned to it is called a wild pointer.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Any attempt to use such uninitialized pointers can cause unexpected behavior, either because the initial value is not a valid address, or because using it may damage other parts of the program.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The result is often a segmentation fault, storage violation or wild branch (if used as a function pointer or branch address).
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In systems with explicit memory allocation, it is possible to create a dangling pointer by deallocating the memory region it points into.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] This type of pointer is dangerous and subtle because a deallocated memory region may contain the same data as it did before it was deallocated but may be then reallocated and overwritten by unrelated code, unknown to the earlier code.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Languages with garbage collection prevent this type of error because deallocation is performed automatically when there are no more references in scope.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In languages that abstract away pointers and pointer arithmetic, such as Java, one can use iterators, which can be seen as a safer means of iterating over a segment of memory or a collection without using direct pointer access.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Many languages, even those with pointers, such as C++, C# and Rust, have iterators for collections.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In C++ the iterator can overload `operator++`, similar to the traditional syntax of incrementing a pointer in C.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Some languages, like C++, support smart pointers, which use a simple form of reference counting to help track allocation of dynamic memory in addition to acting as a reference.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In the absence of reference cycles, where an object refers to itself indirectly through a sequence of smart pointers, these eliminate the possibility of dangling pointers and memory leaks.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Delphi strings support reference counting natively.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The Rust programming language introduces a *borrow checker*, *pointer lifetimes*, and an optimisation based around option types for null pointers to eliminate pointer bugs, without resorting to garbage collection.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] A **null pointer** has a value reserved for indicating that the pointer does not refer to a valid object.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Null pointers are routinely used to represent conditions such as the end of a list of unknown length or the failure to perform some action; this use of null pointers can be compared to nullable types and to the *Nothing* value in an option type.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] A **dangling pointer** is a pointer that does not point to a valid object and consequently may make a program crash or behave oddly.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In the Pascal or C programming languages, pointers that are not specifically initialized may point to unpredictable addresses in memory.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Here, `p2` may point to anywhere in memory, so performing the assignment `*p2 = 'b';` can corrupt an unknown area of memory or trigger a segmentation fault.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Where a pointer is used as the address of the entry point to a program or start of a function which doesn't return anything and is also either uninitialized or corrupted, if a call or jump is nevertheless made to this address, a "wild branch" is said to have occurred.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In other words, a wild branch is a function pointer that is wild (dangling).
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The consequences are usually unpredictable and the error may present itself in several different ways depending upon whether or not the pointer is a "valid" address and whether or not there is (coincidentally) a valid instruction (opcode) at that address.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The detection of a wild branch can present one of the most difficult and frustrating debugging exercises since much of the evidence may already have been destroyed beforehand or by execution of one or more inappropriate instructions at the branch location.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] If available, an instruction set simulator can usually not only detect a wild branch before it takes effect, but also provide a complete or partial trace of its history.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The cited patent also uses the term **self-relative pointer** to mean the same thing.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] A **based pointer** is a pointer whose value is an offset from the value of another pointer.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] This can be used to store and load blocks of data, assigning the address of the beginning of the block to the base pointer.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In some languages, a pointer can reference another pointer, requiring multiple dereference operations to get to the original value.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] While each level of indirection may add a performance cost, it is sometimes necessary in order to provide correct behavior for complex data structures.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] This implementation uses a pointer to the first element in the list as a surrogate for the entire list.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] If a new value is added to the beginning of the list, `head` has to be changed to point to the new element.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In this case, if the value of `item` is less than that of `head`, the caller's `head` is properly updated to the address of the new item.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In some languages, a pointer can reference executable code, i.e., it can point to a function, method, or procedure.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] A function pointer will store the address of a function to be invoked.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] While this facility can be used to call functions dynamically, it is often a favorite technique of virus and other malicious software writers.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In C++, one may use a lambda (anonymous function) in place of a function pointer.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In doubly linked lists or tree structures, a back pointer held on an element 'points back' to the item referring to the current element.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p01] These are useful for navigation and manipulation, at the expense of greater memory use.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Ada is a strongly typed language where all pointers are typed and only safe type conversions are permitted.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] All pointers are by default initialized to `null`, and any attempt to access data through a `null` pointer causes an exception to be raised.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Pointers in Ada are called *access types*.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Ada 83 did not permit arithmetic on access types (although many compiler vendors provided for it as a non-standard feature), but Ada 95 supports “safe” arithmetic on access types via the package `System.Storage_Elements`.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Several old versions of BASIC for the Windows platform had support for `STRPTR()` to return the address of a string, and for `VARPTR()` to return the address of a variable.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Visual Basic 5 also had support for `OBJPTR()` to return the address of an object interface, and for an ADDRESSOF operator to return the address of a function.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] The types of all of these are integers, but their values are equivalent to those held by pointer types.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Newer dialects of BASIC, such as FreeBASIC or BlitzMax, have exhaustive pointer implementations, however.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] In FreeBASIC, arithmetic on ANY pointers (equivalent to C's `void *`) are treated as though the ANY pointer was a byte width.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] ANY pointers cannot be dereferenced, as in C.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Also, casting between ANY and any other type's pointers will not generate any warnings.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] In C pointers are variables that store addresses and can be *null*.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Each pointer has a type it points to, but one can freely cast between pointer types.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] However, it is not possible to cast between a function pointer and an object pointer.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] A special pointer type called the "void pointer" allows pointing to any (non-function) object, but is limited by the fact that it cannot be dereferenced directly.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Pointer arithmetic provides the programmer with a single way of dealing with different types: adding and subtracting the number of elements required instead of the actual offset in bytes.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] In particular, the C standard explicitly declares that the syntax `a[n]`, which is the n-th element of the array `a`, is equivalent to `*(a + n)`, which is the content of the element pointed by `a + n`.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] This implies that, for example, `a[3]` and `3[a]` both access the fourth element of the array `a`.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] While powerful, pointer arithmetic can be a source of computer bugs.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] It tends to confuse novice programmers, forcing them into different contexts: an expression can be an ordinary arithmetic one or a pointer arithmetic one, and sometimes it is easy to mistake one for the other.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] In response to this, many modern high-level computer languages do not permit direct access to memory using addresses.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] The **`void` pointer**, or **`void *`**, is supported in ANSI C as a generic pointer type.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] A pointer to `void` can store the address of any object (not function), and, is implicitly converted to any other object pointer type on assignment, but it must be explicitly cast if dereferenced.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Before ANSI C, K&R used `char *` for the "type-agnostic pointer" purpose.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] C++ fully supports C pointers and C typecasting.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] It also supports a new group of typecasting operators to help catch some unintended dangerous casts at compile-time.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] C++ also supports another form of reference, quite different from a pointer, called simply a *reference* or *reference type*.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Since C++11, the C++ standard library also provides smart pointers, which can be used in some situations as a safer alternative to primitive C pointers.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] `std::unique_ptr` replaces the previous smart pointer std::auto_ptr, which was deprecated in C++11 and removed in C++17.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] In contrast to C, C++ does not allow the implicit conversion of `void*` to other pointer types, even in assignments.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] This was a design decision to avoid careless and even unintended casts, though most compilers only output warnings, not errors, when encountering other casts.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] In C++, there is no `void&` (reference to void) to complement `void*` (pointer to void), because references behave like aliases to the variables they point to, and there can never be a variable whose type is `void`.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] In C++ pointers to non-static members of a class can be defined.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] If a class `MyClass` has a member `T a` then `&MyClass::a` is a pointer to the member `a` of type `T MyClass::*`.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] This member can be an object or a function.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] They can be used on the right-hand side of operators `.*` and `->*` to access the corresponding member.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] The `()` and `[]` have a higher priority than `*`.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] In the C# programming language, pointers are supported by either marking blocks of code that include pointers with the `unsafe` keyword, or through the `System.Runtime.CompilerServices` namespace for pointer access.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] The syntax is essentially the same as in C++, and the address pointed can be either managed or unmanaged memory.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] However, pointers to managed memory (any pointer to a managed object) must be declared using the `fixed` keyword, which prevents the garbage collector from moving the pointed object as part of memory management while the pointer is in scope, thus keeping the pointer address valid.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] However, an exception to this is from using the `IntPtr` structure, which is a memory managed equivalent to `int*`, and does not require the `unsafe` keyword nor the `CompilerServices` assembly.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Most such methods have the same security permission requirements as unmanaged code, since they can affect arbitrary places in memory.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] C# allows stack-allocated arrays in safe code using `System.Span`.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] C#, like C and C++, also has a `void*` (void pointer) type, but it is highly unrecommended.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Unlike C and C++, right-aligned asterisks are not accepted by the compiler.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] In C and C++, this would declare `a` as `int*` and `b` as `int`, but in C# this declares both variables as `int*`.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] The COBOL programming language supports pointers to variables.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Primitive or group (record) data objects declared within the `LINKAGE SECTION` of a program are inherently pointer-based, where the only memory allocated within the program is space for the address of the data item (typically a single memory word).
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] In program source code, these data items are used just like any other `WORKING-STORAGE` variable, but their contents are implicitly accessed indirectly through their `LINKAGE` pointers.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Memory space for each pointed-to data object is typically allocated dynamically using external `CALL` statements or via embedded extended language constructs such as `EXEC CICS` or `EXEC SQL` statements.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Extended versions of COBOL also provide pointer variables declared with `USAGE` `IS` `POINTER` clauses.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] The values of such pointer variables are established and modified using `SET` and `SET` `ADDRESS` statements.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Some extended versions of COBOL also provide `PROCEDURE-POINTER` variables, which are capable of storing the addresses of executable code.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] The PL/I language provides full support for pointers to all data types (including pointers to structures), recursion, multitasking, string handling, and extensive built-in functions.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] PL/I was quite a leap forward compared to the programming languages of its time.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] PL/I pointers are untyped, and therefore no casting is required for pointer dereferencing or assignment.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] The declaration syntax for a pointer is `DECLARE xxx POINTER;`, which declares a pointer named "xxx".
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Pointers are used with `BASED` variables.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] A based variable can be declared with a default locator (`DECLARE xxx BASED(ppp);` or without (`DECLARE xxx BASED;`), where xxx is a based variable, which may be an element variable, a structure, or an array, and ppp is the default pointer).
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Such a variable can be address without an explicit pointer reference (`xxx=1;`, or may be addressed with an explicit reference to the default locator (ppp), or to any other pointer (`qqq->xxx=1;`).
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Pointer arithmetic is not explicitly part of the PL/I standard, but the `UNSPEC` builtin function and pseudo-variable allow pointer arithmetic and many compilers allow expressions of the form `ptr = ptr±expression`.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] IBM PL/I also has the builtin function `PTRADD` to perform the arithmetic.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Pointer arithmetic is always performed in bytes.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] IBM *Enterprise* PL/I compilers have a new form of typed pointer called a `HANDLE`.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] The D programming language is a derivative of C and C++ which fully supports C pointers and C typecasting.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] It supports pointer arithmetic, and also has pointer slices.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] A pointer in D can decay to `void*` implicitly.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] In D, it is possible to use `ref` for a reference, which automatically dereferences, disallows pointer arithmetic, and does not allow escaping a function (i.e. through `return`).
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] A pointer slice can be seen as a pointer with a length.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] The Eiffel object-oriented language employs value and reference semantics without pointer arithmetic.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Nevertheless, pointer classes are provided.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] They offer pointer arithmetic, typecasting, explicit memory management, interfacing with non-Eiffel software, and other features.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Fortran-90 introduced a strongly typed pointer capability.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Fortran pointers contain more than just a simple memory address.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] They also encapsulate the lower and upper bounds of array dimensions, strides (for example, to support arbitrary array sections), and other metadata.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] An *association operator*, `=>` is used to associate a `POINTER` to a variable which has a `TARGET` attribute.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] The Fortran-90 `ALLOCATE` statement may also be used to associate a pointer to a block of memory.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Fortran-2003 adds support for procedure pointers.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Also, as part of the *C Interoperability* feature, Fortran-2003 supports intrinsic functions for converting C-style pointers into Fortran pointers and back.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Go has pointers, declared similar to C/C++ pointers but with the asterisk first.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] For example, a pointer to `T` is written `*T`.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Unlike C, Go has garbage collection, and disallows pointer arithmetic.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Reference types, like in C++, do not exist.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Some built-in types, like maps and channels, are boxed (i.e. internally they are pointers to mutable structures), and are initialized using the `make` function.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] In an approach to unified syntax between pointers and non-pointers, the arrow (`->`) operator has been dropped: the dot operator on a pointer refers to the field or method of the dereferenced object.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] This, however, only works with one level of indirection.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] There is no explicit representation of pointers in Java.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Instead, more complex data structures like objects and arrays are implemented using references.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] The language does not provide any explicit pointer manipulation operators.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] It is still possible for code to attempt to dereference a null reference (null pointer), however, which throws a java.lang.NullPointerException.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] The space occupied by unreferenced memory objects is recovered automatically by garbage collection at run-time.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Java provides the classes `java.lang.ref.WeakReference` and `java.lang.ref.PhantomReference`, which respectively implement weak references and phantom references.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Pointers are implemented very much as in Pascal, as are `VAR` parameters in procedure calls.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Modula-2 is even more strongly typed than Pascal, with fewer ways to escape the type system.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Some of the variants of Modula-2 (such as Modula-3) include garbage collection.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Much as with Modula-2, pointers are available.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] There are still fewer ways to evade the type system and so Oberon and its variants are still safer with respect to pointers than Modula-2 or its variants.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] As with Modula-3, garbage collection is a part of the language specification.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Unlike many languages that feature pointers, standard ISO Pascal only allows pointers to reference dynamically created variables that are anonymous and does not allow them to reference standard static or local variables.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Pointers also must have an associated type and a pointer to one type is not compatible with a pointer to another type (e.g. a pointer to a char is not compatible with a pointer to an integer).
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] This helps eliminate the type security issues inherent with other pointer implementations, particularly those used for PL/I or C.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] It also removes some risks caused by dangling pointers, but the ability to dynamically let go of referenced space by using the `dispose` standard procedure (which has the same effect as the `free` library function found in C) means that the risk of dangling pointers has not been eliminated.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] However, in some commercial and open source Pascal (or derivatives) compiler implementations —like Free Pascal, Turbo Pascal or the Object Pascal in Embarcadero Delphi— a pointer is allowed to reference standard static or local variables and can be cast from one pointer type to another.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Moreover, pointer arithmetic is unrestricted: adding or subtracting from a pointer moves it by that number of bytes in either direction, but using the `Inc` or `Dec` standard procedures with it moves the pointer by the size of the data type it is *declared* to point to.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] An untyped pointer is also provided under the name `Pointer`, which is compatible with other pointer types.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Pointers are declared by use of the dereference operator `^`.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] When it is used in the definition of a variable, the pointer is a reference to a type, which is either intrinsic (defined by the language compiler) or explicitly declared, either in another unit, in the current unit or the main program.
