[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] The Perl programming language supports pointers, although rarely used, in the form of the pack and unpack functions.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] These are intended only for simple interactions with compiled OS libraries.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] In all other cases, Perl uses references, which are typed and do not allow any form of pointer arithmetic.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] They are used to construct complex data structures.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Rust uses references, which are similar to pointers but guaranteed to point to a valid value.
[src:pointer-authentication/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Working with raw pointers is less common, generally for low-level systems programming.
